# Landing pages: rapid to build, good to look at

Landing pages are assembled, not hand-built each time. Speed comes from a shared section library; quality comes from a consistent design bar.

## Build by composition
- Maintain a library of **reusable section components** in `components/sections/`: `Hero`, `LogoCloud`, `FeatureGrid`, `Stats`, `Testimonial`, `Steps`, `FAQ`, `CTA`, plus `Header`/`Footer` in `components/layout/`.
- A new landing page = import sections, pass content via props, order them. Do **not** rebuild bespoke markup per page. If a page needs something the library lacks, add a new reusable section rather than a one-off block.
- Every section is a Server Component and takes its copy/data as props (keeps it reusable and server-rendered).

## Design bar (what "looks good" means here)
- **Generous whitespace.** Give sections room; crowding reads as cheap.
- **Clear type hierarchy.** One obvious H1, a supporting sub-head, readable body. Limit to two typefaces and a defined size scale.
- **One primary call to action per view.** Secondary actions are visually quieter.
- **Consistent rhythm.** Use the spacing scale from `tailwind.config` for section padding and gaps, so vertical rhythm is even down the page.
- **Real content, never lorem.** Design against the actual headline and copy, since length changes the layout.
- **Match the design reference.** When a layout or visual reference is supplied (for example an AI Studio export or screenshot), replicate its structure, spacing, colour, and typography faithfully unless asked to change it.
- Above-the-fold hero image uses `next/image` with `priority`; everything else lazy-loads.

## Responsive and stable
- Design mobile-first, then scale up. Test the hero and nav at 375px width.
- Reserve space for media and late-loading content so nothing shifts (protects CLS).

## Guardrail
Every landing page still passes the SEO and accessibility rules: one H1, semantic sections, unique metadata, alt text, answer-first copy. Fast to build does not mean skipping those.
